{
  "doc_id": "48522",
  "text": "Previous study revealed the molecular target, epidermal growth factor receptor (EGFR), was highly expressed in more than 80% of locoregionally advanced NPC patients and correlated with poor clinical outcome. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] Cetuximab (CTX), an anti-EGFR antibody, had been proven to improve survival of locoregionally advanced head and neck squamous cell carcinoma patients when combined with radiotherapy. [CITATION_3] When radiation increased the expression of EGFR in NPC cells, inhibition of EGFR signaling made tumor cells more sensitive to radiotherapy. [CITATION_4] Ma and his colleagues had shown a single-arm phase II clinical trial and reported that addition of CTX to concurrent chemoradiotherapy for locoregionally advanced NPC was a feasible strategy. [CITATION_5] He and his colleagues had observed that combination of CTX and chemoradiotherapy was effective and tolerated. [CITATION_6] These findings prompted researchers to investigate whether patients of locoregionally advanced NPC could benefit from the concurrent combination of CTX plus chemoradiotherapy.",
